Q: context transition
A: An animation that maintains user context by showing how the new state originates from the previous one.

---

Q: drill transition
A: Used in hierarchical navigation; an animation where the view moves forward into deeper content or backward out of it, often using sliding or scaling.

---

Q: tween/interpoloation
A: The process of generating intermediate frames (in-betweening) to create the illusion of smooth motion.

---

Q: origin-aware animation
A: Animations that emanate from the exact interaction point (e.g., where the user tapped or clicked) to reinforce causality.

---

Q: crossfade
A: A simultaneous transition where one element fades out while another fades in.

---

Q: morph
A: Seamlessly transforming the shape, size, or properties of one UI element into another.

---

Q: layout animation
A: Animating the reflow of elements when the DOM structure changes or elements are resized.

---

Q: direction-aware transition
A: An animation that adapts its directional motion (e.g., slide left vs right) based on the user's trajectory or interaction logic.

---

Q: rubber-banding
A: An overscroll effect where the UI stretches and snaps back to indicate the end of a scrolling boundary.

---

Q: rippling
A: A radial expansion effect starting from the point of contact, providing visual feedback for a touch or click.

---

Q: asymmetric easing
A: Using different easing curves for the enter and exit states (e.g., entering with deceleration, exiting with acceleration).

---

Q: text morph and clip-path
A: Animating typographic changes or revealing content using CSS clip-path transitions.

---

Q: number ticker
A: Animating numerical changes by rolling or sliding individual digits, similar to an odometer.

---

Q: Layout thrashing
A: A performance bottleneck caused by repeatedly reading and writing DOM layout properties in quick succession, forcing the browser to recalculate synchronous layouts.

---

Q: Spatial consistency
A: Designing transitions so that elements maintain logical spatial relationships, making the interface behave like physical objects.

---

Q: `[&|?]curius=\v\d+(,\s*\d+)*//g`
A: grepping all curius queries within a HTTP link

---

Q: `\v\((O[^|]*)\)(\s*\|)/$\1$\2/g`
A: Grepping any text that starts with a capital letter O, followed by some characters, and ends with a vertical bar/pipe character (|)

---

Q: `sudo pmset -b sleep 0; sudo pmset -b disablesleep 1`
A: disable display sleeping MacOS

---

Q: `sudo pmset -b sleep 5; sudo pmset -b disablesleep 0`
A: revert sleeping setup on MacOS

---

Q: SAXPY
A: single-precision a \* x plus y

---

Q: L1 BLAS
A: scalar,vector,vector-vector ops

---

Q: L2 BLAS
A: matrix-vector ops

---

Q: L3 BLAS
A: matrix-matrix ops

---

Q: Big O notation
A:
$$\begin{aligned} &\text{Big O(micron)}: O \text{ or } \mathcal{O} \\ &\text{Big Omega}: \Omega \\ &\text{Big Theta}: \Theta \\ &\text{Small O(micron)}: o \\ &\text{Small Omega}: \omega \\ &\text{On the order of}: \sim \end{aligned}$$

---

Q: time complexity of algorithm
A:
| Algorithm | Best | Average | Worst | Stable | In-place |
| -------------- | ------------ | ------------ | ------------ | ------- | -------- |
| Bubble Sort | $O(n)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(n^2)$ | Yes | Yes |
| Selection Sort | $O(n^2)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(n^2)$ | No | Yes |
| Insertion Sort | $O(n)$ | $O(n^2)$ | $O(n^2)$ | Yes | Yes |
| Merge Sort | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | Yes | No |
| Quick Sort | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n^2)$ | No | Yes-ish |
| Heap Sort | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | No | Yes |
| Counting Sort | $O(n+k)$ | $O(n+k)$ | $O(n+k)$ | Yes | No |
| Radix Sort | $O(d(n+k))$ | $O(d(n+k))$ | $O(d(n+k))$ | Yes | No |
| Bucket Sort | $O(n+k)$ | $O(n+k)$ | $O(n^2)$ | Depends | Depends |
| TimSort | $O(n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | $O(n\log n)$ | Yes | No-ish |

---

Q: saudade
A: a feeling of longing, melancholy, or nostalgia that is supposedly characteristic of Portuguese temperament

---

Q: fin de siècle
A: relating to or characteristic of the end of a century, especially the 19th century.

---

Q: quine
A: is a computer program that takes no input and produces a copy of its own _source code_ as its only output.

---

Q: endogenous
A: having an internal cause or origin

---

Q: joie de vivre
A: exuberant enjoyment of life

---

Q: ditering
A: quantized color on the web

---

Q: gastronomy
A: art of choosing, cooking, and eating good food.

---

Q: la cuisine nouvelle
A: characterized by lighter, more delicate dishes and an increased emphasis on presentation

---

Q: haute cuisine
A: meticulous preparation, elaborate presentation, and the use of high quality ingredients

---

Q: liminal space
A: the in-between/transition state of being, see also [[thoughts/aesthetic value|aesthetics]]

---

Q: polyphony
A: a feature of narrative, which includes a diversity of simultaneous points of view and voices

---

Q: row-major memory locations
A:
$$x + N_x \cdot y$$
- Access `A[y][x]`

---

Q: col-major memory locations
A:
$$y + N_y \cdot (x-1)$$
- Access `A(y, x)`

---

Q: polysyllabic
A: words with many syllables, often used to define complex terminology

---

Q: triptych
A: a picture/relief carving on three panels, typically hinged together side by side and used as an altarpiece

---

Q: lex parsimoniae
A: also known as law of parsimony, circa Occam's razor

---

Q: kalsarikännit
A: drink alone in your underwear with no intention of going out

---

Q: stork
A: Baby-bringing bird

---

Q: pesky
A: annoying to deal with

---

Q: lowkenuinely
A: lowkey + genuinely

---

Q: a fortiori
A: mostly used to lead from a less certain proposition to a more evident corollary, i.e. "even more so"

---

Q: passementerie
A: fancy decorations on clothes

---

Q: claudification
A: the [[library/Phenomenology of Perception|phenomena]] where Claude Code "harnesses" tasks by attributing a verb describing what it is doing.

---

Q: semiotic
A: the study of signs

---

Q: chauvinist
A: a person who displays an aggressive, unreasonable, and fanatical belief in the superiority of their own group

---

Q: truculent
A: someone who is aggressively self-assertive, defiant, and easily angered

---

Q: Euler's polyhedron formula
A: $V-E+F$

---

Q: mnestics
A: see also [lesswrong](https://www.lesswrong.com/s/YshDJ9ECCgkwoNsBc/p/ksatPnddyZjHwZWwG), but largely this term comes from the book [[library/There is No Antimemetics Division|There is No Antimemetics Division]] by qntm

---

Q: portmanteau
A: In literature, also known in linguistics and lexicography as a blend word, lexical blend, or simply a blend, is a word formed by combining the meanings and parts of the sounds of two or more words.

---

Q: solipsistic
A: the philosophical belief that only one's own mind is sure to exist. In every day language, it can be interpreted as self-centered, self-absorbed

---

Q: errata
A: a list of corrections or errors discovered in a published work

---

Q: lingua franca
A: a language systematically adopted as a common medium of communication between speakers whose native languages differ; a bridge language

---

Q: CPU operation cost ladder
A: A modern x86/x64 ballpark where operations span from `<1` cycle for register-register work to `10,000-1,000,000` cycles for a full thread context switch.

---

Q: CPU operation cost caveat
A: Treat the numbers as order-of-magnitude estimates; exact timings depend on CPU, compiler, cache state, contention, and surrounding instructions.

---

Q: CPU cost: simple register-register op
A: `<1` cycle for `ADD`, `OR`, `MOV`-like work when operands are already in registers.

---

Q: CPU cost: memory write
A: `~1` cycle apparent cost when the CPU can buffer the write.

---

Q: CPU cost: bypass delay
A: `0-3` cycles to switch between integer and floating-point units.

---

Q: CPU cost: correctly predicted branch
A: `1-2` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: floating-point/vector addition
A: `1-3` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: multiplication
A: `1-7` cycles for integer, floating-point, or vector multiplication.

---

Q: CPU cost: return error code and check
A: `1-7` cycles in the normal case.

---

Q: CPU cost: L1 read
A: `3-4` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: TLB miss
A: `7-21` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: L2 read
A: `10-12` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: branch misprediction
A: `10-20` cycles, roughly `5-20x` the correctly predicted branch path.

---

Q: CPU cost: floating-point division
A: `10-40` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: 128-bit vector division
A: `10-70` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: atomics/CAS
A: `15-30` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: C function direct call
A: `15-30` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: integer division
A: `15-40` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: C function indirect call
A: `20-50` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: C++ virtual function call
A: `30-60` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: L3 read
A: `30-70` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: main RAM read
A: `100-150` cycles, roughly `30-50x` an L1 read.

---

Q: CPU cost: NUMA different-socket atomics/CAS
A: `100-300` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: NUMA different-socket L3 read
A: `100-300` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: allocation+deallocation pair
A: `200-500` cycles for small objects.

---

Q: CPU cost: NUMA different-socket main RAM read
A: `300-500` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: kernel call
A: `1,000-1,500` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: thread context switch direct costs
A: `2,000` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: C++ exception thrown+caught
A: `5,000-10,000` cycles.

---

Q: CPU cost: thread context switch total costs
A: `10,000-1,000,000` cycles, including cache invalidation.

---

Q: Torschlusspanik
A: German, literally "gate-shut panic"; the anxiety that time is running out to act, especially the fear of diminishing opportunities (love, career, milestones) as one grows older.

---

Q: Kairos
A: Ancient Greek for the opportune or decisive moment, the right time to act; contrasted with _chronos_ (sequential clock time), and in rhetoric the moment ripe for persuasion.

---

Q: pêche à pied
A: French, "fishing on foot"; gathering shellfish and other seafood by hand along the foreshore at low tide.

---

Q: tomfoolering
A: foolish or silly behaviour; acting the fool (gerund of tomfoolery).

---

Q: ostreperous
A: (obstreperous) noisy, unruly, and difficult to control.

---

Q: carthusian
A: a member of the Carthusian order, an austere contemplative Catholic order founded by St Bruno in 1084, known for silence and solitude.

---

Q: vaudeville
A: a genre of variety entertainment popular in North America in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, made up of separate unrelated acts.

---

Q: firmament
A: the heavens or the sky, especially regarded as a vault or arch.

---

Q: nipper
A: British informal for a young child; also the pincer claw of a crab or lobster.

---

Q: aspersion
A: an attack on someone's reputation; a damaging or derogatory remark, as in "cast aspersions".

---

Q: eudaimonia
A: Greek for human flourishing or the highest human good; in Aristotelian ethics, well-being achieved through living virtuously.

---

Q: vim
A: energy and enthusiasm, as in "vim and vigour".

---

Q: sibilant
A: making or characterized by a hissing sound, such as s, sh, or z.

---

Q: nomenclature
A: the system or set of names used in a particular field; the act of devising or choosing names.

---

Q: inundation
A: a flood; an overwhelming abundance or influx of something.

---

Q: paratactic
A: relating to parataxis; placing clauses or phrases one after another without coordinating or subordinating connectives.

---

Q: blogosphere
A: the collective community of all blogs and their authors.

---

Q: smitheeren
A: (smithereens) small fragments or pieces, as in "blown to smithereens".

---

Q: bloviating
A: talking at length in an inflated, pompous, and empty way.

---

Q: POSIWID
A: "the purpose of a system is what it does"; a systems-thinking principle (Stafford Beer) that a system's real purpose is revealed by its actual behaviour, not its stated goals.

---

Q: sacrament
A: a religious rite regarded as imparting divine grace (e.g. baptism, the Eucharist); something regarded as sacred.

---

Q: muggy
A: (of weather) unpleasantly warm and humid.

---

Q: dasein
A: German for "being-there"; Heidegger's term for the distinctively human mode of existence that is aware of and questions its own being.

---

Q: amatonormativity
A: the assumption that a central, exclusive romantic relationship is a universal goal and normative for everyone (coined by Elizabeth Brake).

---

Q: epistolary
A: relating to letters; (of a literary work) written in the form of letters.

---

Q: meliorism
A: the belief that the world can be improved by human effort; a middle position between optimism and pessimism.

---

Q: ample
A: enough or more than enough; plentiful.

---

Q: interlocutors
A: people who take part in a dialogue or conversation.

---

Q: a priori
A: relating to reasoning that proceeds from theoretical deduction rather than observation; knowledge independent of experience.

---

Q: jovial
A: cheerful and good-humoured.

---

Q: iconoclastic
A: characterized by attacking cherished beliefs or established institutions; originally, destroying religious images.

---

Q: quixotic
A: extremely idealistic, unrealistic, and impractical (after Don Quixote).

---

Q: asinine
A: extremely stupid or foolish.

---

Q: peleton
A: (peloton) the main group of riders bunched together in a cycling race.

---

Q: domestique
A: a road cyclist who works for the benefit of their team and leader rather than to win.

---

Q: fevor
A: (fervour) intense and passionate feeling.

---

Q: preclude
A: to prevent from happening; to make impossible.

---

Q: revenant
A: a person who has returned, especially supposedly from the dead.

---

Q: moratorium
A: a temporary prohibition or suspension of an activity; a legal authorization to delay payment.

---

Q: pervasive
A: spreading widely throughout an area or group; present everywhere.

---

Q: continuity transition
A: An animation that carries a shared element across states so the interface reads as one continuous object rather than a cut between screens. See [gabriell_lab](https://x.com/gabriell_lab/status/2058217175047901310).

---

Q: `/^\s*-\s*tags:\s*\[/s/\(\[[^]]*\)\zs\([a-z0-9]\+\)-\([a-z0-9]\+\)\ze[^]]*\]/\2 \3/g`
A: On lines matching a `tags: [...]` array, replace the hyphen in each hyphenated lowercase-alphanumeric tag (e.g. `foo-bar` becomes `foo bar`) with a space, leaving the surrounding brackets untouched.

---

Q: myopic
A: nearsighted (short-sighted vision); figuratively, lacking foresight or breadth of view, focused only on immediate concerns.

---

Q: latency numbers everyone should know
A: Finbarr Timbers' rule-of-thumb table spanning `1 ns` for an L1 cache reference to `150 ms` for a TCP round trip between continents, a ~150,000,000:1 spread; orders of magnitude matter more than the exact figures.

---

Q: latency: L1 cache reference
A: `1 ns` (`0.000001 ms`).

---

Q: latency: branch misprediction
A: `3 ns`, roughly `3x` an L1 cache reference.

---

Q: latency: L2 cache reference
A: `4 ns`, roughly `4x` an L1 cache reference.

---

Q: latency: mutex lock/unlock
A: `17 ns`.

---

Q: latency: main memory reference
A: `100 ns`, roughly `100x` an L1 cache reference.

---

Q: latency: compress 1 kB with Zippy
A: `2,000 ns` (`0.002 ms`).

---

Q: latency: send 2 kB over 10 Gbps network
A: `1,600 ns` (`0.0016 ms`).

---

Q: latency: read 1 MB sequentially from memory
A: `10,000 ns` (`0.01 ms`).

---

Q: latency: SSD 4 kB random read
A: `20,000 ns` (`0.02 ms`).

---

Q: latency: read 1 MB sequentially from SSD
A: `1,000,000 ns` (`1 ms`), roughly `100x` reading 1 MB from memory.

---

Q: latency: round trip within same datacenter
A: `500,000 ns` (`0.5 ms`).

---

Q: latency: read 1 MB sequentially from disk
A: `5,000,000 ns` (`5 ms`), roughly `5x` reading 1 MB from SSD.

---

Q: latency: read 1 MB sequentially from 1 Gbps network
A: `10,000,000 ns` (`10 ms`).

---

Q: latency: disk seek
A: `10,000,000 ns` (`10 ms`).

---

Q: latency: TCP packet round trip between continents
A: `150,000,000 ns` (`150 ms`), the most expensive entry, roughly `300x` a same-datacenter round trip.

---

Q: throughput: sequential read from HDD
A: `~200 MB/s`.

---

Q: throughput: sequential read from SSD
A: `~1 GB/s`, roughly `5x` HDD sequential read.

---

Q: throughput: sequential read from main memory
A: `~100 GB/s` burst.

---

Q: throughput: sequential read from 10 Gbps Ethernet
A: `~1000 MB/s`.

---

Q: round trips: Europe to US
A: `~6-7/s`, limited by the cross-continent round-trip latency.

---

Q: round trips: same-datacenter
A: `~2000/s`, roughly `300x` the Europe-to-US rate.

---

Q: latency sample calculation: 30 × 256 kB images from one server
A: With 2 disks/machine, `30 / 2 = 15` reads; one HDD image read is `(256 kB / 1 MB) * 5ms + 10ms seek = 1.28ms + 10ms = 11.28ms`; total `15 * 11.28ms = 169.2ms`, giving `1000 / 169.2 ≈ 5` result pages/s.

---

Q: subaqueous
A: existing, formed, or taking place under water.

---

Q: rollicking
A: exuberantly lively and amusing; boisterously carefree.

---

Q: consign
A: to deliver to someone's custody or care; to send (goods) to a destination, especially for sale; to assign to a place or state, often an undesirable one, as in "consign to oblivion".

---

Q: mitochondrial biogenesis
A: the process by which cells increase mitochondrial mass and number through growth and division of pre-existing mitochondria; regulated by PGC-1α and triggered by endurance exercise, caloric restriction, and cold exposure.
